Sessions

A session is server-side storage that keeps track of a user’s login state.
Server creates a session (e.g., session_id)
Stores user data on the server (memory, DB, Redis)
Sends the session ID to the client (usually via a cookie)


Cookies
A cookie is a small piece of data stored in the browser.
Sent automatically with every request to the server
Can store session IDs, JWTs, or other data


JWT (JSON Web Token)
A JWT is a self-contained token that includes user info and is signed.
Stored on client (cookie, localStorage, etc.)
Sent with each request (usually in headers)
Server verifies signature instead of storing session


Stateful vs Stateless Authentication
Type	    Description
Stateful	Server stores user session data
Stateless	Server stores nothing; client sends all info

Sessions → Stateful
JWT → Stateless



3. Authentication Flow Diagrams


Session-Based Authentication Flow

[User Login]
     ↓
[Server validates credentials]
     ↓
[Server creates session + session_id]
     ↓
[session_id sent via cookie]
     ↓
[Browser stores cookie]

Next Requests:
[Browser → sends cookie]
     ↓
[Server looks up session_id]
     ↓
[User authenticated]


JWT Authentication Flow
[User Login]
     ↓
[Server validates credentials]
     ↓
[Server creates JWT]
     ↓
[JWT sent to client]
     ↓
[Client stores JWT]

Next Requests:
[Client sends JWT (header/cookie)]
     ↓
[Server verifies signature]
     ↓
[User authenticated]



Session vs JWT Comparison
| Feature     | Sessions                      | JWT                       |
| ----------- | ----------------------------- | ------------------------- |
| Storage     | Server-side                   | Client-side               |
| Type        | Stateful                      | Stateless                 |
| Scalability | Harder (needs shared storage) | Easier (no server memory) |
| Performance | Slightly slower (DB lookup)   | Faster (no lookup)        |
| Revocation  | Easy (delete session)         | Hard (token still valid)  |
| Security    | More controlled               | Depends on storage method |
| Size        | Small (session ID)            | Larger (payload included) |
| Best for    | Traditional web apps          | APIs, microservices       |


| Concept                     | Sessions | JWT         |
| --------------------------- | -------- | ----------- |
| Who stores user data?       | Server   | Client      |
| Needs database lookup?      | Yes      | No          |
| Easy logout everywhere?     | Yes      | No (harder) |
| Works well across services? | No       | Yes         |


Where Cookies Fit In
Cookies are just a transport mechanism, not an auth system.

When to Use Each
✅ Use Sessions When:
You have a traditional web app
You need easy logout / revocation
You want strong control over user state
Example:
Admin dashboards
Banking apps

✅ Use JWT When:
You’re building APIs / microservices
You need scalability
You have mobile + web clients
Example:
REST APIs
Mobile apps


Real-World Decision Guide
👉 Choose Sessions if:
You control the backend tightly
Simplicity > scalability

👉 Choose JWT if:
You need distributed systems
You want stateless architecture

👉 Combine JWT + Cookies if:
You want stateless auth + browser security


